<%- include('partials/header') %>

    <div class="page-container">
        <div class="page-header">
            <h1>📂 File Viewer</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Vulnerability: Local File Inclusion / Path Traversal (A01:2021)</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
            <form method="GET" action="/read">
                <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="file">File to Read (from public folder)</label>
                    <input type="text" id="file" name="file" class="form-control" placeholder="e.g. style.css" required value="<%= typeof selectedFile !== 'undefined' ? selectedFile : '' %>">
                </div>
                <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">📖 Read File</button>
            </form>
        </div>

        <% if (typeof content !== 'undefined') { %>
            <div class="output-box">
                <div class="output-header">📄 File Contents (<%= selectedFile %>)</div>
                <div class="output-body">
                    <% if (error) { %>
                        <span style="color: red;"><%= error %></span>
                    <% } else { %>
                        <pre style="white-space: pre-wrap; font-family: monospace; font-size: 14px; margin: 0;"><%= content %></pre>
                    <% } %>
                </div>
            </div>
        <% } %>

        <div class="hint-box">
            <button class="hint-toggle">💡 Show Attack Hints</button>
            <div class="hint-content">
                <h4>🧠 How LFI / Path Traversal Works</h4>
                <p>
                    This tool lets you read files from the server's <code>public</code> directory. However, it blindly joins the path you provide with the base directory without checking if the resulting path stays within the <code>public</code> directory. You can use <code>../</code> to go up a folder and read files outside of the intended directory.
                </p>

                <h4 class="mt-2">🎯 Try These Payloads</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>../package.json</code> — Reads the Node.js project file</li>
                    <li><code>../server.js</code> — Reads the backend source code</li>
                    <li><code>../../../../../../etc/passwd</code> — Reads the system password file on Linux</li>
                    <li><code>../vulnerable.db</code> — Downloads or reads the SQLite database!</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h4 class="mt-2">🛡️ How to Fix It</h4>
                <p>Ensure that the resolved file path starts with the intended base directory.
                    For example, using <code>path.resolve</code> and checking if it <code>startsWith</code> the public folder's absolute path.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <%- include('partials/footer') %>
